  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "Glycolysis in E. coli is the central pathway for glucose catabolism, converting one glucose molecule to two pyruvate molecules while producing 2 ATP (net) and 2 NADH. The pathway consists of 10 enzyme-catalyzed steps divided into two phases: the energy investment phase (steps 1-5, consuming 2 ATP) and the energy payoff phase (steps 6-10, producing 4 ATP and 2 NADH). E. coli has metabolic flexibility with alternative enzymes at several steps: glucose can enter via phosphotransferase system (PTS) or permease, different phosphofructokinases exist (Pfk-1 and Pfk-2), and pyruvate has multiple fates (TCA cycle, fermentation, or biosynthesis). The pathway is regulated by allosteric effectors (PEP inhibits Pfk, AMP activates), phosphorylation, and transcriptional control. This flowchart illustrates the complete pathway, alternative routes, regulatory mechanisms, and metabolic branch points.",
  "id": "ecoli_glycolysis",
