  "name": "Glycolysis (Embden-Meyerhof-Parnas Pathway)",
  "notGates": 1,
  "notes": "Glycolysis is the most ancient and conserved metabolic pathway, present in nearly all organisms. E. coli's version has bacterial-specific features including PTS for glucose uptake and Pfk-2 as an alternative phosphofructokinase. The pathway demonstrates metabolic flexibility with pyruvate having multiple fates (oxidation, fermentation, biosynthesis) depending on oxygen availability. Phosphofructokinase (Pfk) is the committed and rate-limiting step, subject to allosteric regulation by energy charge. Under anaerobiosis, E. coli performs mixed-acid fermentation producing lactate, ethanol, formate, and acetate to regenerate NAD+ for continued glycolysis. The pathway is essential for both catabolism and anabolism, providing precursors for biosynthesis.",
  "organism": "E. coli",
